Expectations for this workshop

  • Prereqs
    • Basic knowledge of R
    • RStudio installed on your machine
    • The following packages: tidyverse, ggplot2, sf, ggspatial
  • Helpful but not required
    • Familiarity with the tidyverse and ggplot2
    • Experience with GIS

Objectives

  • You’ll leave with…
    • An example map using vector data
    • Code you can adapt for your own projects
  • We won’t cover…
    • Geospatial analysis
    • Raster data

Why use R for map-making?

  • Advantages
    • Free and open-source
    • Easy to integrate with your R projects
    • Modifiable - make tweaks, toggle layers
    • Modulable - spin out figures for different end-points
  • Disadvantages
    • Need to script changes, can’t just point-and-click
    • Some features difficult to integrate (e.g., basemaps)

Workflow

  1. Ideate - Sketch out what you want, get feedback
  2. Gather - Gather the data you need
  3. Set up - Set up your R workspace
  4. Prepare - Prepare the data
  5. Visualize - Visualize the features you’re interested in
  6. Order - Decide on order of layers
  7. Construct - Map each layer, one at a time
  8. Stack - Put the layers together
  9. Style - color, texture, details, axes, scale bar, north arrow
  10. Finalize - labels, other finishing touches
  11. Share

1. Ideate

  • Sketch out what you want
  • Get feedback
  • We’ll skip this for today’s purposes, but helpful to do before putting in the time to code!
  • For today’s workshop, let’s make a map that shows census tracts by CalEnviroScreen score overlaid with air quality monitor points, showing magnitude of fine particulate matter (PM2.5)

2. Gather

  • Identify the datasets you need
  • Your data (whatever you’re working on and want to share)
  • Cities, landmarks, administrative boundaries (counties, states/provinces, countries), etc.
  • For today’s workshop, we’ll use the following datasets:
    • Shapefile data from the California Communities Environmental Health Screening Tool, CalEnviroScreen 3.0
    • Locations of air quality monitors from the California Air Resources Board (CARB)
    • Mapping files for administrative boundaries from the U.S. Census Bureau

3. Set up

  • Open up RStudio
  • Start a directory with your R script, add the data
  • Load the relevant packges (and install them if you haven’t already)
# if you don't have the packages below installed, use this line
#install.packages(c("tidyverse", "ggplot2", "sf", "ggspatial", "viridis"))

# loads relevant packages
library(tidyverse)  # broad range of functions for data manipulation
library(ggplot2)    # for plotting (fyi, included in 'tidyverse')
library(sf)         # useful package for GIS operations
library(ggspatial)  # for adding map scales, north arrow
library(viridis)    # color-blind friendly color palettes

4. Prepare

  • Download data for the workshop from this GitHub repo
  • Define coordinate reference system (CRS)
  • Import the data
# defines coordinate reference system (CRS), for map projection
project_crs <- st_crs("+init=epsg:4269 +proj=longlat +ellps=GRS80
                       +datum=NAD83 +no_defs +towgs84=0,0,0")  

# imports the datasets and matches all coordinate reference systems
cal_enviro <- st_read("data/cal_enviro.shp") %>% st_transform(project_crs)
cal_counties <- st_read("data/cal_counties.shp") %>% st_transform(project_crs)
carb_monitors <- st_read("data/carb_monitors.shp") %>% st_transform(project_crs)
us_states <- st_read("data/us_states.shp") %>% st_transform(project_crs)
world_countries <- st_read("data/world_countries.shp") %>% st_transform(project_crs)

5. Visualize

# plots the data we have, e.g., census tract polygons, to make sure it looks right
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_geometry(cal_enviro)) 

# note: 'geom_sf()' is a ggplot geom specifically for sf objects, i.e.,
#       spatial features imported using the 'sf' package
# note: 'st_geometry()' strips everything but the vector data

5. Visualize, part 2

# adds layer with location of CARB air quality monitors to census tracts
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_geometry(cal_enviro)) +
  geom_sf(data = carb_monitors, aes(color = AIRDISTRIC)) + # color by air district
  theme(legend.position = "none") # drops legend (we don't need it right now)

# note: notice how we need to point to a different data source within each
#       'geom_sf' call; if we define a data source within the ggplot() call,
#       the layering won't work

6. Order

  • Decide on order of layers
  • For this map, let’s do the following (in order):
    • Layer 1: neighboring states (as basemap)
    • Layer 2: neighboring country (also as basemap)
    • Layer 3: census tracts shaded by CalEnviroScreen decilee
    • Layer 4: outline of California state boundary
    • Layer 5: points for air monitors with size linked to mean PM2.5 concentration

7. Construct

# Map each layer, one at a time.  It's a good idea to plot each layer 
# to make sure it looks right this is redundant for some of the layers,
# but I find it helpful to have a consistent naming system, e.g.,
# when working with the data for other purposes

# layer - census tracts in the top 10% for CalEnviroScreen score; these
#         are defined as 'environmental justice' communities in this dataset
  lyr_cal_enviro <- cal_enviro %>% select(CIdecile)
# layer - air quality monitors points data; let's spatially join these data
#         to the 'cal_enviro' dataset (a step that's outside the scope of this
#         workshop) so we can manipulate the size by mean PM2.5 pollution levels
  lyr_monitors <- carb_monitors %>% st_join(cal_enviro) %>% select(pmP) %>% drop_na()
# layer - California state boundary; binds counties together 
  lyr_california <- cal_counties %>% st_union() %>% st_geometry()
# layer - states
  lyr_states <- us_states %>%
    filter(NAME %in% c("Oregon", "Idaho", "Nevada", "Arizona", "Utah")) %>% 
    st_geometry()
# layer - world countries (for map inset)
  lyr_countries <- world_countries %>% 
    filter(CNTRY_NAME %in% c("Mexico")) %>%
    st_geometry()

8. Stack

# put the layers together!
my_map <-  ggplot() +
  # layer 1 - neighboring states shaded gray with slightly darker outline
  geom_sf(data = lyr_states, fill = "gray80", color = "gray70") +
  # layer 2 - neighboring country, shaded darker gray with slightly darker outline
  geom_sf(data = lyr_countries, fill = "gray60", color = "gray50") +
  # layer 3 - census tracts shaded by CalEnviroScreen decile
  geom_sf(data = lyr_cal_enviro, aes(fill = as.factor(CIdecile)), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis(alpha = 0.6, discrete = TRUE) +
  # layer 4 - outline of California state boundaries with black border
  geom_sf(data = lyr_california, fill = NA, color = "#000000") +
  # layer 5 - air monitors with size determined by PM2.5 percentile
  geom_sf(data = lyr_monitors, aes(size = pmP), alpha = 0.15) +
  # sets x-axis (longitude) and y-axis (latitude) viewer range
  xlim(c(-125, -114)) + ylim(c(32.2, 42.2)) +
  # makes the negative space (i.e., background) blue
  theme(panel.grid = element_line(color = "#ADD8E6"),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#ADD8E6"),
        legend.position = "none") # drops legend (we don't need it right now))

8. Stack, part 2

9. Style

Let’s add details like a scale bar and north arrow

my_map <- my_map +
  # adds scale bar to bottom left ('bl')
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.4) +
  # adds north arrow top right ('tr')
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "tr", which_north = "true", 
                         style = north_arrow_minimal) +
  theme_bw() + # adds outline to panel
  # need to add this code again as it was nullified by the above line
  theme(panel.grid = element_line(color = "#ADD8E6"),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#ADD8E6"),
        legend.position = "none") # drops legend (we don't need it right now))

9. Style, part 2

10. Finalize

  • Add labels, position legend, other finishing touches
  • Place map inset, highlight area of focus
  • Can be difficult to get just right with R
  • A vector graphics editor is great for this
  • E.g., Adobe Illustrator, InkScape (free alternative)
